SIMPLE: give
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Give
<hw>Give</hw> <pr>(g⟦icr⟧v)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Gave</conjf> <pr>(g⟦amac⟧v)</pr>;
<pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Given</conjf> <pr>(g⟦icr⟧v"'n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Giving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>given</ets>, <ets>yiven</ets>, <ets>yeven</ets>, AS.
<ets>gifan</ets>, <ets>giefan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>geven</ets>, OS.
<ets>ge⟦edh⟧an</ets>, OHG. <ets>geban</ets>, G. <ets>geben</ets>, Icel.
<ets>gefa</ets>, Sw. <ets>gifva</ets>, Dan. <ets>give</ets>, Goth.
<ets>giban</ets>. Cf. <er>Gift</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To bestow without receiving a return; to confer without
compensation; to impart, as a possession; to grant, as authority or
permission; to yield up or allow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For generous lords had rather <qex>give</qex> than pay.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To yield possesion of; to deliver over, as property,
in exchange for something; to pay; <as>as, we <ex>give</ex> the value of
what we buy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What shall a man <qex>give</qex> in exchange for his soul ?</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xvi. 26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To yield; to furnish; to produce; to emit; <as>as,
flint and steel <ex>give</ex> sparks</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To communicate or announce, as advice, tidings,
etc.; to pronounce; to render or utter, as an opinion, a judgment, a
sentence, a shout, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To grant power or license to; to permit; to allow;
to license; to commission.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is <qex>given</qex> me once again to behold my friend.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then <qex>give</qex> thy friend to shed the sacred wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To exhibit as a product or result; to produce; to
show; <as>as, the number of men, divided by the number of ships,
<ex>gives</ex> four hundred to each ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To devote; to apply; used reflexively, to devote or
apply one's self; <as>as, the soldiers <ex>give</ex> themselves to
plunder</as>; also in this sense used very frequently in the past
participle; <as>as, the people are <ex>given</ex> to luxury and
pleasure; the youth is <ex>given</ex> to study.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Logic & Math.)</fld> <def>To set forth as a known
quantity or a known relation, or as a premise from which to reason; --
used principally in the passive form <xex>given</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To allow or admit by way of supposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>give</qex> not heaven for lost.</q>
<rj><qau>Mlton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To attribute; to assign; to adjudge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I don't wonder at people's <qex>giving</qex> him to me as a
lover.</q> <rj><qau>Sheridan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To excite or cause to exist, as a sensation;
<as>as, to <ex>give</ex> offense; to <ex>give</ex> pleasure or
pain.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>To pledge; <as>as, to <ex>give</ex> one's
word</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>To cause; to make; -- with the infinitive; <as>as,
to <ex>give</ex> one to understand, to know, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But there the duke was <qex>given</qex> to understand⟦br⟧
That in a gondola were seen together⟦br⟧
Lorenzo and his amorous Jessica.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>To afford a view of; <as>as, his window
<ex>gave</ex> the park</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To give away</b></col>, <cd>to make over to another; to
transfer.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatsoever we employ in charitable uses during our lives, is
<qex>given away</qex> from ourselves.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To give back</b></col>, <cd>to return; to restore.</cd>
<au>Atterbury.</au> -- <col><b>To give the bag</b></col>, <cd>to
cheat.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I fear our ears have <qex>given</qex> us <qex>the bag</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Webster.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To give birth to</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To bear or
bring forth, as a child.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To originate; to give
existence to, as an enterprise, idea.</cd> -- <col><b>To give
chase</b></col>, <cd>to pursue.</cd> -- <col><b>To give ear
to</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Ear</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To give
forth</b></col>, <cd>to give out; to publish; to tell.</cd>
<au>Hayward.</au> -- <col><b>To give ground</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Ground</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To give the
hand</b></col>, <cd>to pledge friendship or faith.</cd> -- <col><b>To
give the hand of</b></col>, <cd>to espouse; to bestow in marriage.</cd>
-- <col><b>To give the head</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Head</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To give in</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
abate; to deduct.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To declare; to make known; to
announce; to tender; <as>as, <ex>to give in</ex> one's adhesion to a
party</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To give the lie to</b></col> <cd>(a person),
to tell (him) that he lies.</cd> -- <col><b>To give line</b></col>.
<cd>See under <er>Line</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To give off</b></col>,
<cd>to emit, as steam, vapor, odor, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>To give one's
self away</b></col>, <cd>to make an inconsiderate surrender of one's
cause, an unintentional disclosure of one's purposes, or the like.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To give out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To utter publicly; to report; to announce or declare.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One that <qex>gives out</qex> himself Prince Florizel.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Give out</qex> you are of Epidamnum.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To send out; to emit; to distribute; as, a substance
<xex>gives out</xex> steam or odors.</cd> -- <col><b>To give
over</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To yield completely; to quit; to
abandon.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To despair of.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To
addict, resign, or apply (one's self).</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Babylonians had <qex>given</qex> themselves <qex>over</qex> to
all manner of vice.</q> <rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To give place</b></col>, <cd>to withdraw; to yield one's
claim.</cd> -- <col><b>To give points</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In
games of skill, to equalize chances by conceding a certain advantage; to
allow a handicap.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To give useful suggestions.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To give rein</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Rein</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To give the sack</b></col>.
<cd>Same as <cref>To give the bag</cref>.</cd> -- <col><b>To give and
take</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To average gains and losses.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To exchange freely, as blows, sarcasms, etc.</cd> --
<col><b>To give time</b></col> <sd>(Law)</sd>, <cd>to accord extension
or forbearance to a debtor.</cd> <au>Abbott.</au> -- <col><b>To give the
time of day</b></col>, <cd>to salute one with the compliment appropriate
to the hour, as ⟦ldquo⟧good morning.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧good evening⟦rdquo⟧,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>To give tongue</b></col>, <cd>in hunter's phrase,
to bark; -- said of dogs.</cd> -- <col><b>To give up</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To abandon; to surrender. ⟦ldquo⟧Don't <xex>give
up</xex> the ship.⟦rdquo⟧</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He has . . . <qex>given up</qex>⟦br⟧
For certain drops of salt, your city Rome.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To make public; to reveal.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll not state them⟦br⟧
By <qex>giving up</qex> their characters.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <cd>(Used also reflexively.</cd>) -- <col><b>To give up
the ghost</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Ghost</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To
give one's self up</b></col>, <cd>to abandon hope; to despair; to
surrender one's self.</cd> -- <col><b>To give way</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To withdraw; to give place.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
yield to force or pressure; as, the scaffolding <xex>gave
way</xex>.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To begin to row; or
to row with increased energy.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Stock
Exchange)</fld>. <cd>To depreciate or decline in value; as, railroad
securities <xex>gave way</xex> two per cent.</cd> -- <col><b>To give way
together</b></col>, <cd>to row in time; to keep stroke.</cd></p></cs>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To <er>Give</er>, <er>Confer</er>,
<er>Grant</er>.</syn> <usage> To <xex>give</xex> is the generic word,
embracing all the rest. To <xex>confer</xex> was originally used of
persons in power, who gave permanent grants or privileges; as, to
<xex>confer</xex> the order of knighthood; and hence it still denotes
the giving of something which might have been withheld; as, to
<xex>confer</xex> a favor. To <xex>grant</xex> is to give in answer to a
petition or request, or to one who is in some way dependent or
inferior.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Give</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Give
<hw>Give</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To give a
gift or gifts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To yield to force or pressure; to relax; to become
less rigid; <as>as, the earth <ex>gives</ex> under the
feet</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To become soft or moist.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon .</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To move; to recede.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now back he <qex>gives</qex>, then rushes on amain.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To shed tears; to weep.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose eyes do never <qex>give</qex>⟦br⟧
But through lust and laughter.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To have a misgiving.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My mind <qex>gives</qex> ye're reserved⟦br⟧
To rob poor market women.</q> <rj><qau>J. Webster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To open; to lead.</def> <mark>[A
Gallicism]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This, yielding, <qex>gave</qex> into a grassy walk.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To give back</b></col>, <cd>to recede; to retire; to
retreat.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>gave back</qex> and came no farther.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To give in</b></col>, <cd>to yield; to succumb; to
acknowledge one's self beaten; to cease opposition.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Scots battalion was enforced to <qex>give in</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This consideration may induce a translator to <qex>give in</qex>
to those general phrases.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To give off</b></col>, <cd>to cease; to forbear.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Locke.</au> -- <col><b>To give on</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To give upon</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To rush; to
fall upon.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To have a view of;
to be in sight of; to overlook; to look toward; to open upon; to front;
to face.</cd> <mark>[A Gallicism: <plain>cf. Fr.</plain> donner
sur.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rooms which <qex>gave upon</qex> a pillared porch.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The gloomy staircase <qex>on</qex> which the grating
<qex>gave</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To give out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To expend all
one's strength.</cd> Hence: <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To cease from exertion; to
fail; to be exhausted; as, my feet being <xex>to give out</xex>; the
flour has <xex>given out</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>To give over</b></col>,
<cd>to cease; to discontinue; to desist.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It would be well for all authors, if they knew when <qex>to give
over</qex>, and to desist from any further pursuits after fame.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To give up</b></col>, <cd>to cease from effort; to yield;
to despair; as, he would never <xex>give up</xex>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>give-and-go</ent>⟦br⟧
